<section xml:id="lesson5_3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
     <title>Quantum State Representations</title>

In this lesson, we will introduce how classical computers store state, followed
by quantum computers.
<section xml:id="classical_state" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
     <title>Classical State Representations</title>

<p> Everything in a computer is stored as a number.</p>

Everything is stored as a number in a variable:

The color of the font of this sentence



<p>
<ul>
<li>Each letter of this sentence (s is 115, S is 83) </li>
<li>The font sizes of different kinds of text (titles vs normal text)</li>
<li>The images included in this online book (lots and lots of numbers indicating the color of each pixel)</li>
<li>Sounds from an audio file </li>
</ul>
</p>

<p> All of these numbers are stored in binary, which is base 2.</p>


<sidebyside widths="50% 50%" valign="top">
    <p>
<ul>
<li>A binary digit holds a 1 or a 0 (at any given time) </li>
<li>A binary digit is called a bit</li>
<li>4 bits is a nibble, 8 bits is a byte</li>
</ul>
</p>
 
    <image source="L5.1-nibble.png" width="66%" />
</sidebyside>



</section>

<section xml:id="bra_ket_state" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
     <title>Bra-Ket Quantum Representation</title>

<p> The purpose of Bra-Ket notation is to express the probability of each potential outcome.
Therefore, there are two parts: The probability and the outcome.</p>

<p> Bra-ket notation  favors ease of calculation over easy readability of the probability, 
but it is easier to read than its alternative, vector notation.</p>

<p> Each outcome is expressed in a "ket" -  (replace with math symbols 
that are more true to the accurate ones).
 </p>

<sidebyside widths="50% 50%" valign="top">
    <p>
In the figure to the right, we are expressing the probabilities 
of measuring apples or bananas. The outcome (apple or banana) is 
placed inside of the ket, and the probability magnitude 
(rather than the probability) is placed as a term just before the ket.
The relationship between probability amplitude and probability is that
the probability = |probability amplitude| squared.  (put in math) 

</p>
 
    <image source="L5.3.braket.png" width="66%" />
</sidebyside>

<p> In this notation, if there is equal probability, or 1/2 probability of each of two outcomes,
then it will be: </p>

<p> picture like the one above with apples and bananas but with the terms 1/rt(2) for each </p>

<p> Put in a question here using heads or tails coins in bra-ket notation and ask what the 
probability is of each outcome.</p>


<p> If we want to express two outcomes (such as the raincoat / raining example from before), 
it would look like the following:</p>

